<section id="stakes" class="py-[var(--spacing-section)] border-t border-slate-gray">
  <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 lg:px-12">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="font-heading text-titanium-white mb-8" style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-4xl); line-height: 1.05; letter-spacing: -0.02em;" data-animate="headline">
        Here's what nobody in this industry talks about.
      </h2>
    </div>
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto space-y-6" data-animate="fade" data-animate-delay="1">
      <p class="font-body text-soft-gray" style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-base); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
        Most muralists paint what they want to paint. They walk in with a style. Your wall becomes another canvas for their portfolio. Your story? That's secondary. Their art comes first.
      </p>
      <p class="font-body text-soft-gray" style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-base); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
        Sign shops work the other way around. Speed and volume. They take your logo, print it on vinyl, slap it on the building, and move to the next job. Your sign is a transaction. Nobody asks what it should mean.
      </p>
      <p class="font-body text-soft-gray" style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-base); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
        Both produce work that looks fine. Nobody stops for it. Nobody photographs it. Nobody walks in because of it.
      </p>
      <p class="font-body text-titanium-white" style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-base); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
        That's what happens when the meaning gets skipped.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
